Palestine responds to Israel: We will destroy all previous agreements
Palestinian President Mahmoud Abbas announced Thursday at the UN General Assembly session that he would break all agreements with Israel if the country's future government tries to meet Benjamin Netanyahu's announcement of annexation of the occupied Palestinian territories.
"If the future government of Israel, which will be formed, proceeds to implement this plan, we will nullify all the agreements signed (with Israel) and withdraw from all the commitments made," he declared.
"We will completely and completely reject the whole plan," Abbas threatened under pressure.
“It is our duty to defend all our rights by all possible means – no matter what the consequences – by fully engaging in the application of international law and the fight against terrorism,” declared the President of the Palestinian Authority, who had already made similar declarations in July.
Netanyahu, the current prime minister of Israel, was again given the task of forming a government after the September 17 elections.
A week before the election, he announced that if he won, he would announce the annexation of the Jordan Valley and that he intended to incorporate all Jewish settlements in the West Bank into Israel.
In the early 1990s, Israel and the Palestinians, then led by Yasser Arafat, signed a series of peace agreements sponsored by the United States.
The 84-year-old Abbas also promised during the session of the UN General Assembly to hold general elections in Palestinian lands.
The last one took place in 2006.
“After returning to the country, I call for local elections in the West Bank, Gaza and East Jerusalem, and anyone who opposes them will have to answer for their actions before God and the international community,” the Palestinian president solemnly declared.
Abbas also defended in his speech the rights of Palestine, treated as a permanent observer in the UN, to exercise the powers of "full members of the UN and all its organs and institutions".
The Palestinian leader concluded by calling on the international community to "force Israel to comply with the United Nations resolutions with full respect".
Israeli Ambassador Danny Danon briefly responded to Abbas' speech, stating that the Palestinian leader "wants to focus in the UN on the efforts of the Palestinian Authority against Israel, rather than to fight the calls for terrorism in the Authority under his leadership".
However, Danon did not refer to Netanyahu's annexation of the occupied Palestinian territories.
