PLN 105 million for companies from the video game industry from the National Centre for Research and Development
Almost PLN 105 million of co-financing will go to companies from the gaming industry, creating innovative solutions.
The National Centre for Research and Development announced on Friday the results of the third edition of the GameINN programme.
Among the nearly 30 projects supported by NCBR were: the development of a platform for creating terrain games based on an AR game engine that creates a map of the real world together with an application that allows users to transfer data; a test and training platform for verifying practical skills in the workplace and professional development using VR and AI technologies; an innovative game simulating the management of real production processes using an innovative gameplay model based on the interaction of the virtual world with the real world using the concept of Industry 4.0 – stated in the NCBR communication sent to PAP on Friday.
The aim of the GameINN sector programme is to increase the competitiveness of the Polish video game industry on the global market by 2023.
According to NCBR, the Polish video game sector is already growing at a rate of 10% per year.
According to government data, the value of the Polish video game market in 2016 amounted to PLN 1.85 billion, while the forecast for 2019 is PLN 2.23 billion.
“The specially prepared GameINN research agenda and the already PLN 300 million support for entrepreneurs under this sectoral programme provide an important impetus for the further, dynamic growth of Polish gamedev,” reads the communication.
The video game industry is an excellent example of effective use of the potential that we have in Poland.
"The incentives introduced by the government for entrepreneurs who are committed to innovation, such as R&D concessions, competence improvement programs, IP boxes or support programs implemented by NCBR, drive the innovative activity of companies and allow them to compete more effectively on a very competitive market," says Deputy Prime Minister, Minister of Science and Higher Education Jarosław Gowin, quoted in the communication.
The head of the Ministry of Science points out that the money for innovation not only goes to innovators in the form of project funding, but also remains in their pockets – three quarters more entrepreneurs benefited from the R&D rebate in 2018 than a year earlier.
"The amount of deducted costs for R&D activities amounted to PLN 1.7 billion, which resulted in savings of over PLN 300 million for companies benefiting from this rebate.
This is the equivalent of the support provided by NCBR in three editions of GameINN”, emphasizes the Deputy Prime Minister.
NCBR Director Wojciech Kamieniecki reminds that 78 innovative projects were awarded in two previous competitions with a total value of over PLN 211.2 million.
The great interest in the III competition and the variety of applications show that the video game industry has ideas and competences to further develop and increase its competitive advantages.
“I am particularly pleased that among the selected projects – as in previous editions – there are projects concerning solutions not only for entertainment, but also related to Industry 4.0,” he adds.
In the third GameINN competition, entrepreneurs, a consortium of entrepreneurs and a consortium of entrepreneurs with scientific units could apply for funding of up to PLN 20 million.
The NCBR received 87 applications for a total amount of approx. PLN 317 million.
The budget of the competition at the time of the announcement of the competition was PLN 100 million, but it was increased, so that 27 projects were granted almost PLN 105 million of co-financing.
Detailed information about the results of GameINN III competition is available on the website ncbr.gov.pl.
The GameINN sector programme is implemented as part of the Intelligent Development Operational Programme.
NCBR launched the program in 2016 in response to an initiative of entrepreneurs associated with the Polish Games Alliance, which includes companies such as CD Projekt, Techland, CI Games, Bloober Team and 11 bit studios.
