On July 4, the American Independence Day, journalist Mariusz Max Kolonko, who was in the USA, announced the formation of a new political formation - #R Revolution.
In recent years, Kolonko has become famous for running the Max TV channel on YouTube, where he comments on events in Poland and around the world.
“We’ve had enough of politicians, enough of your harsh jokes, enough of your amateur governments.
It is time for the nation to take power in the country and to govern for the good of the nation,” Kolonko said at the time.
The party's program included issues related to the judiciary (should be elected in general elections), tax changes (equalization of the tax-free amount for all), war reparations (in the form of military aid for the countries of the eastern flanks of NATO, with particular emphasis on Poland), conducting a referendum on the possession of weapons, limiting the number of deputies or introducing single-member constituencies.
A few days after the announcement of the formation of a new political formation, Mariusz Max Kolonko entered into talks with Marek Jakubiak.
At the end of July, Kolonko posted on his social media profile information suggesting that #R would join forces with the Kukiz'15 movement.
However, none of these coalitions ultimately came to fruition.
UBS: Gold close to equilibrium
“The euro exchange rate will remain around PLN 4.35 in the coming months, which will be accompanied by a weak situation on the global markets,” says Michael Bolliger from UBS Wealth Management.
“The expectations of maintaining a solid economic growth rate and a stable monetary policy speak in favour of stabilising the gold prices at the current ceiling,” the specialist in an interview with Bankier.pl estimates.
In his opinion, despite the clear inflationary pressure, the Monetary Policy Council will not decide on interest rate increases in an environment in which the vast majority of central banks are relaxing policy.
“If the zloty is properly valued – the euro should remain in the range of PLN 4.35 in the coming months – Polish bonds are not very attractive.
Far more profitable than Polish securities are emerging market bonds,” says Michael Bolliger, head of asset allocation for emerging markets at UBS Wealth Management.
According to the expert, the main threat to the Polish economy is the deterioration of the global economic situation.
“The global slowdown may deepen, but it should not lead to a severe recession, or at most to a fall in GDP dynamics slightly below zero,” says Michael Bolliger.
"Investors should not underestimate global stocks, which could be damaged by the lack of prospects for resolving the US-China trade conflict and other geopolitical risk factors, including Donald Trump's impeachment procedure and Brexit.
Among the stock markets, Europe should be the relatively weakest”, according to the latest investor letter from UBS Wealth Management CEO Mark Haefele.
"The actions of the countries of the euro area should behave worse than the Americans, because they are more vulnerable in the conditions of increased uncertainty around global trade and fears of a slowdown", we read in the document.
In the opinion of Michael Bolliger, after the hossa on the bond markets of the safest countries pushed the profitability of German 10-year bonds even to minus 0.74 percent, it is still possible to deepen the decline in profitability.
In the longer term, however, the profitability of long-term securities should no longer fall, but only of short-term securities, thanks to the easing of banks' monetary policy.
The Fed has the largest scope for rate cuts, which should weaken the US currency in the coming years.
The long-term equilibrium for the euro is a ceiling of USD 1.29, which would mean a 19-percent potential strengthening of the common currency against the dollar.
