“42% of the species of trees that make up Europe’s forests are threatened,” warns the International Union for Conservation of Nature (IUCN) in Friday’s Red Book of European Trees.
At the head of the list are, among others, chestnuts and hawksbills.
The IUCN, based in Gland, Switzerland, is publishing a list of endangered species of European trees for the first time.
It was compiled by specialists who, based on research, concluded that of the 454 species of trees found in Europe (as well as in other parts of the world), 42% are "highly endangered".
Among the causes, the Red Book mentions the rapid growth of urban agglomerations and global climate change.
However, the most threatened are those trees and shrubs that occur only or mainly on our continent.
As far as the typical European tree stand is concerned, according to IUCN experts, 58% of species are at risk and 15%, i.e. 66 species of trees and shrubs, are threatened with extinction.
Among the main causes of deforestation, the Red Book lists errors in the exploitation of forest stands, accelerated urbanisation, excessive cutting of trees, followed by forest fires and changes in the European ecosystem.
According to the authors of the report, the existence of many European varieties of shrubs, mosses and stands is also seriously threatened.
“The consequences of human activities are leading to the gradual extinction of European plant species and are threatening to extinguish important and undervalued varieties in Europe, which form the basis of European ecosystems and affect the health of our planet,” concluded Luc Bas, Director of the European Office of the IUCN.
