GUS: Life in Poland is getting better
According to the report on household budgets published on Friday by the Central Statistical Office, as many as 44% of households rated their material situation as good or rather good.
A year earlier, this percentage was 37.2%, in 2016 it was 33.5%, and previously – since 2009, when the statistical office first examined subjective assessments of the situation of households – it never exceeded 30%.
A total of 8.1% of households considered their material situation to be bad or rather bad, compared to 11.2% a year earlier and more than 20% in 2009.
The best is the material situation of households of self-employed persons.
In this group, it is considered good or rather good by more than 70% of respondents.
On the other extreme are the pensioners' households, where the percentage of such responses was only 18%.
The number of children also has a big influence on the subjective assessment of the material situation of households.
The worst situation is experienced by parents who raise their children alone, of whom 32% declare a good or rather good material situation.
Among couples with children, this percentage varies (depending on the number of children) from 55 to 60 per cent, and among households without children it is 48.8 per cent.
The effect of the 500+ programme is clearly visible in these statistics.
Before it was launched (in 2016), the worst assessment of their material situation was made by parents raising their children alone and families with many children (with at least three children).
Improving subjective assessments of the material situation of Poles is a reflection of the rapid growth in income, especially from work.
However, this is not all, because the percentage of households that consider their situation to be good is increasing faster than real income.
Furthermore, at the level of voivodships there is no clear correlation between the level of income and the assessment of the material conditions of households.
The best assessments are made by the inhabitants of the Opole Voivodeship, where 48.9% of respondents consider their situation to be good or rather good.
Further there are Lubuskie Voivodeships (47.7%), Silesian Voivodeships (47.6%), Mazowieckie Voivodeships (47.3%) and Zachodniopomorskie Voivodeships (47.1%).
Meanwhile, in Opolskie the disposable income (i.e. after paying taxes and contributions) amounted to less than 94% of the national average, and in Lubusz 98%.
The highest incomes were inhabitants of Mazowieckie (120% of the national average) and Silesia (104%).
On average in Poland, the disposable income per person amounted to PLN 1693 in 2018.
In real terms (after adjustment for the impact of price changes) it increased by 4.3% compared to 2017.
Compared to previous years, this result is quite low.
In 2016, per capita income increased by 7%, and a year later by 6.3%.
While income growth slows down, it also hampers spending growth.
These amounted to PLN 1187 per person, which means that in real terms they decreased by 0.7%.
This is the first such case since 2013.
In 2017, expenditure per person increased in real terms by 1.9%, and in 2016 by 4.3%.
Surveys of household budgets suggest that statistical households currently spend 70.1% of their disposable income, whereas in 2014 this share exceeded 80% and by 2006 it exceeded 90%.
