"Rzeczpospolita": Ignoring a policeman's orders will be punished
According to the newspaper, disregarding a police officer's order for specific behaviour is to be a new type of offence, threatened with fines, arrest or imprisonment.
The political trade unionists want to introduce such a change.
The idea went to the Sejm Committee on Petitions.
“The case is serious, because already every year more than half a million criminal cases reach Polish courts,” we read.
"Rzeczpospolita" has determined that the petition, which the Independent Trade Union of Policemen writes to MPs on the amendment of the Code of Offences has a chance of success.
The authors of the petition propose a new wording of Article 54a of the Code of Offences.
It would read: "Whoever does not comply with the request or order of a public official issued within the limits and on the basis of the provisions of the Act, shall be subject to arrest, fine or restriction of liberty."
"Paragraph 3 of this provision provides for an identical punishment for those who, by failing to execute orders, prevent or hinder the performance of their duties," the daily reports.
Sociologist Andrzej Kowalski told "Rzeczpospolita" that although he agrees with the main message of the proposal, he fears that if it is implemented, it may be used in matters of political demonstrations.
“In situations of freedom demonstrations it would be unfavourable and instead of alleviating the situation, it would even exacerbate it,” he adds.
According to statistics provided by the newspaper, 86% of citizens positively assessed police interventions in 2018 and that every month the services undertake 1.5 million interventions in the city.
Buras worries about Europe
Jáchym Topol has writing in his blood.
Among his ancestors are editors, translators, writers.
His father, Josef Topol, was one of the most important Czech post-war playwrights, today listed in the same row as Václav Havel.
From the beginning, therefore, there was a curse of talent hanging over Jáchym, which he tries to use.
After eight years, he returned with "The Sensitive Man".
The protagonists are Buras and Soňa together with their two sons, who do not form a typical Czech family.
They are wandering actors, they travel around Europe.
He is a lover of Shakespeare and a thief, she is a one-eyed translator who does not break up with a bottle of wine.
One of the boys from birth did not make a sound, and for the other time stopped in childhood.
But it is not the heroes who are the most important in this story.
All of them are merely a background for observing a world in which there is no longer room for artistic nomads.
It is a world of a flooded province, a society of old, suspicious people and disconnected youth.
“Sensitive Man” sometimes turns into absurd theatre.
The narrative follows the didaskalia, and the conversations of the characters create this world.
The scene is a Europe full of worries about its future, but also of constant questions about the past.
Belgium: Brussels Airlines cancelled 105 flights due to the bankruptcy of Thomas Cook
Although the British travel agency Thomas Cook has collapsed, its Belgian subsidiary Neckermann is functioning.
However, the company has problems.
According to VRT, Brussels Airlines has announced that it will cancel 105 flights in October due to problems related to the bankruptcy of Thomas Cook.
Neckermann also laid off 75 employees.
All office trips that have been booked in Belgium will be cancelled, but holidaymakers will be able to receive a refund.
The court in Ghent also declared the bankruptcy of three Belgian subsidiaries: Thomas Cook Belgium, Thomas Cook Retail and Thomas Cook Financial Services.
Currently, around 12,000 Belgians are abroad on trips purchased from Thomas Cook.
Another 40,000 people were to leave the office by the end of the year.
On Monday, Thomas Cook Belgium spokeswoman Leen Segers said that the company is now "fully operational" despite the announcement of bankruptcy by the British parent company, which caused concern among employees and customers.
At that time, the office was reassuring that customers who bought tours in it would go on holiday.
Thomas Cook – the oldest and one of the largest travel agencies in the world – announced bankruptcy on the night of Sunday to Monday.
The immediate cause of the bankruptcy was the collapse of last chance talks with creditors and potential investors on Sunday.
The creditors demanded that, in addition to the £900 million rescue plan already agreed in August, the company obtain an additional £200 million as collateral for the winter period, when travel agencies usually have lower turnover.
However, the company's problems have grown over the years, resulting in a debt of £1.6 billion.
