Görlitz in Germany offers free accommodation per review
Free accommodation in exchange for an opinion – such an extraordinary offer prepared for the new German Görlitz.
The measures are intended to help combat the progressive decline in the number of inhabitants of the city.
Görlitz is the easternmost city in Germany.
The beautiful pastel old town attracts 140 thousand tourists every year.
However, according to The Guardian, the city faces significant challenges.
Görlitz has the lowest wages in Germany.
The city is also experiencing a steady decline in population.
After the fall of the Berlin Wall in 1989, most of them moved to the west of the country, resulting in a 25% decline in the city's population.
In 2013 it had 54,000 inhabitants.
In order to combat depopulation, officials came up with the idea of offering free monthly accommodation in the city.
So far, 150 applications have been received for the programme.
Two-thirds of them were inhabitants of large cities.
People from Hungary, the Czech Republic, the United States and the United Kingdom also took an interest in the programme.
“When we implemented the programme, we thought that it would convince people to move to Görlitz,” said one of the project participants.
“Now we feel it doesn’t matter whether we stay here after four weeks or not,” he added.
The city has seven thousand vacant dwellings and unemployment is three times higher than the national average.
Although the city authorities hope that some will move permanently, the main aim of the programme is to obtain the opinions of the participants.
The information gathered from interviews and questionnaires is intended to help revitalise smaller German cities.
“We want to know more about what people need and, if they decide to move, what their motivation was,” said Robert Knippschild, programme manager.
Other cities have already experimented with ideas to attract new residents, offering them incentives in the form of accommodation.
The first was Detroit, which introduced a program to pay promising young professionals to live and work in the city for a year.
Today, such solutions are used in many places, from the Greek island of Antikythera to Candela in Italy, or in Tulsa, Oklahoma.
